The article discusses the importance of recognizing and supporting the rights of Black Americans with disabilities. It emphasizes that Black History Month should also celebrate the resilience and talents of Black disabled individuals. The article acknowledges that although America was founded on the principle of equality, racism and ableism have been long-standing barriers for Black people with disabilities. The Biden-Harris Administration is commended for taking historic action to advance equity through various measures such as executive orders, administrative actions, and funding. The government is examining policies and programs for disparities that hinder the full participation and independence of Black disabled individuals. The article concludes by stating that while progress has been made, there is still work to be done to create an inclusive, accessible, and equitable nation.